The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Monday, May 10, 2004  The City Diary
																																																		Three people lost their lives under the wheels of vehicles in the city and Howrah over the past 24 hours. A 35-year-old man, identified as Bhabatosh Das, was run over by a lorry on Saturday night while he was walking down Raja Dinendra Street. Police said Das, a resident of Canal West Road, was taken to RG Kar Medical College and Hospital, where he was declared dead. The vehicle was impounded and the driver arrested. In the second mishap, 50-year old Dipak Das was run over by a tanker near Bataitola, in the Shibpur police station area of Howrah, on Saturday evening. Das was a resident of Mourigram. Tapas Pal, 32, was run over by a truck in Barasat on Saturday night. Pal was crossing the busy Jerut Road when the lorry, travelling at a high speed, knocked him down. The driver sped away after the mishap. 																																																		Train services on the Howrah-Burdwan chord line of Eastern Railways Howrah division were disrupted for more than two hours on Sunday after a goods train jumped the rails. A railway spokesperson said at around 3 pm, two empty wagons at the rear of the train got derailed while the train was being pulled out of the Howrah sorting yard. The derailed wagons blocked the chord line and the Up Howrah-Burdwan Main line. The Main line was cleared by 3.53 pm, but the chord line was blocked till 5.30 pm, the spokesperson said.																																																		Kishore Das, 19, drowned in Rabindra Sarobar while bathing on Sunday. Das bathed in the Lakes regularly and around 1 pm on Sunday, he arrived for his swim. When he failed to emerge from the water, a rescue attempt was mounted. Das lifeless body was fished out. He was a resident of Sukanta Nagar.							TO THE ONCOLOGISTS from the city and across the country who held a seminar on lung cancer and its treatment on Saturday
